{"parentUuid":"8f6d7de3-f93a-4c64-90b1-3724999b5cb0","isSidechain":false,"message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_019DDZDSxaiWQFeky2dW6etP","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_019whGVQFph88nNe42wGUf49","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"marvin work","description":"Run marvin work to print/launch implementation prompt"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":6,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1123,"cache_read_input_tokens":39663,"output_tokens":208,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1123,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[{"input_tokens":6,"output_tokens":208,"cache_read_input_tokens":39663,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1123,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1123},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CaabizQJpDsDKryTtgVK3","attributionSkill":"marvin:marvin","attributionPlugin":"marvin","type":"assistant","uuid":"c5675957-3051-4cab-b89e-e57a63014729","timestamp":"2026-04-30T20:38:07.983Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/alisha/Projects/skills","sessionId":"a88641f6-df38-4dda-89ef-d14176b173e6","version":"2.1.123","gitBranch":"alisha/commit"}
{"parentUuid":"c5675957-3051-4cab-b89e-e57a63014729","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"2b92bb35-2200-4dda-ae8b-cbba73f37ecb","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019whGVQFph88nNe42wGUf49","type":"tool_result","content":"You are working in the current repo on a marvin plan.\n\nYour task: implement the plan below in this worktree. Commit your work as you\ngo with small, focused commits and clear messages. Do NOT push.\n\nPlan lives at docs/plans/entire-commit-push-pr-plan.md and is reproduced below for convenience:\n\n---\n\n# Plan: `entire`-powered commit + push + PR skill\n\n## Goal\n\nShip a new skill in this repo (`/Users/alisha/Projects/skills`) that does the\nsame job as the upstream `commit-commands:commit-push-pr` (commit local\nchanges, push, open a draft PR) but generates the commit message **and** the\nPR title/description from `entire` checkpoint data instead of `git diff` /\n`git log`.\n\n## Why\n\nThe git-only path summarizes *what changed*. `entire` knows *why* it changed —\nthe prompts, the intent, the things tried and abandoned during the agent\nsession. That context produces better PR descriptions and reviewable commits,\nespecially for agent-driven work.\n\n## Reference: existing skill\n\nUpstream skill:\n`~/.claude/plugins/marketplaces/claude-plugins-official/plugins/commit-commands/commands/commit-push-pr.md`\n\nIt is ~20 lines. It builds context from `git status` + `git diff HEAD` and\ntells the model to commit, push, and `gh pr create` in a single message. It\nis delivered as a Claude-Code slash command with strict `allowed-tools`\nfrontmatter.\n\n## Hard constraints\n\n1. `entire search` hits a server-side index and is **forbidden** — unpushed\n   local checkpoints are not indexed there. This skill MUST use only local\n   data. Permitted commands:\n   - `entire explain --commit <sha> --short --no-pager` — per-commit intent\n     pulled from local session transcripts. **Primary source.**\n   - `entire explain --commit <sha> --no-pager` — fuller per-commit context if\n     `--short` is too thin for the title decision.\n   - `entire explain <checkpoint-id> --short --no-pager` — optional checkpoint\n     detail for the most recent current-branch checkpoint when synthesizing a\n     commit message for newly staged but uncommitted work.\n   - `entire dispatch --local --since <window>` — prose summary of recent agent\n     work for the current branch. **Optional tiebreaker only** (see\n     §\"Design choice: per-commit, not dispatch\" below).\n   - `entire activity` / `entire sessions` — not used in the core flow.\n\n2. Always pass `--no-pager` to `entire explain` calls so explain output stays\n   non-interactive in agent shells. Do not invent `--no-pager` on commands that\n   do not support it (for example `entire dispatch`).\n\n3. Use the installed `entire` from `PATH`, not a `./entire` checked into the\n   repo.\n\n## Design choice: per-commit, not dispatch\n\nThe earlier draft proposed `entire dispatch --local` as the primary source for\nthe PR title and body summary. I'm pushing back. Reasons:\n\n- `dispatch` is **time-window scoped** (`--since`/`--until`), not commit-range\n  scoped. A branch that sat for a few days alongside other work will pull in\n  unrelated agent activity from sibling branches.\n- `dispatch` is designed for standup-style activity reports, not for \"describe\n  this set of commits\".\n- Per-commit `entire explain --commit <sha> --short` already gives precise,\n  branch-scoped context. Aggregating those across the push range is more\n  faithful to the actual diff being reviewed.\n\n**Decision:** the skill aggregates `entire explain --commit <sha> --short` for\nevery commit in the push range. `entire dispatch --local` is only invoked as a\nfallback when the push range has more than `MAX_PER_COMMIT_LOOKUPS` commits\n(proposed cap: 10). In every other case, dispatch is skipped. (An earlier draft\nalso suggested falling back to dispatch when every per-commit lookup returned\n\"no checkpoint\"; that trigger was dropped because dispatch reads the same\ncheckpoint store and would be equally empty.)\n\n## Behavior the skill should produce\n\nThe skill executes the following sequence. Independent commands inside a step\nshould be batched in parallel where the host agent supports it.\n\n### 1. Sanity / preflight\n\n- Run `entire version` and `gh --version`. If `entire` is missing → fall back\n  to git-only path (see §Fallback). If `gh` is missing → stop with a clear\n  error.\n- Run `git rev-parse --is-inside-work-tree`. If not in a repo, stop.\n- Determine the base branch:\n  1. `gh repo view --json defaultBranchRef -q .defaultBranchRef.name` if\n     authenticated.\n  2. Otherwise `git symbolic-ref --short refs/remotes/origin/HEAD` and strip\n     the `origin/` prefix.\n  3. Otherwise `main`.\n- Compute the merge-base: `git merge-base origin/<base> HEAD`. If\n  `origin/<base>` is missing, fetch it once with `git fetch origin <base>` and\n  retry. If still missing, stop and ask the user.\n- Do **not** finalize the push range yet if the working tree is dirty. A new\n  commit created in Step 3 would otherwise be missing from the PR summary.\n\n### 2. Branch from `main` if needed\n\nIf the current branch IS the base branch, create a new branch first. Derive the\nbranch name from the same heuristics later used for the commit message seed in\nStep 3, sanitized to `kebab-case` and prefixed with `agent/`. If that seed is\nempty or too vague, fall back to `agent/<YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS>`. Do not ask the user\nto pick a branch name in v1.\n\n### 3. Stage + commit any uncommitted work\n\n- `git status --porcelain` to detect uncommitted changes. Skip this step if\n  clean.\n- Stage with explicit paths (no `git add -A`/`git add .`) per the user's\n  global git-safety rules.\n- Build the commit message seed:\n  - First inspect `entire explain --no-pager` list output for the newest\n    checkpoint on the current branch. If a relevant checkpoint is present, run\n    `entire explain <checkpoint-id> --short --no-pager` and use its intent line\n    as the seed.\n  - If there is no relevant checkpoint, or the checkpoint intent clearly does\n    not match the staged diff, fall back to a `git diff --staged` summary (same\n    path the upstream skill takes).\n- `git commit -m \"$(cat <<'EOF' ... EOF)\"` with the standard `Co-Authored-By`\n  trailer.\n- After committing, recompute the push range with\n  `git log --reverse --format=%H <merge-base>..HEAD` so the freshly created\n  commit is included in the PR content.\n\n### 4. Push\n\n- `git push -u origin HEAD`.\n\n### 5. Build the PR content\n\n- For each commit SHA in the push range, run in parallel:\n  `entire explain --commit <sha> --short --no-pager`.\n- Deduplicate per-checkpoint output where multiple commits share a checkpoint.\n- For each commit, classify the result:\n  - `checkpoint-backed` — has an intent/summary line.\n  - `no-checkpoint` — commit was authored outside an Entire session (human\n    commit, manual rebase, etc.). Detected by matching the literal output\n    `No associated Entire checkpoint` (or its `--short` equivalent), or by a\n    zero-exit run that produced no intent line. Use the commit message subject\n    verbatim.\n  - `lookup-failed` — non-zero exit. Log to stderr, treat as `no-checkpoint`.\n\n- **Title** — derived from the *most recent* `checkpoint-backed` commit's\n  intent, trimmed to ≤70 chars. If no commit is checkpoint-backed, fall back\n  to the upstream skill's git-derived title.\n- If **zero** commits in the push range are `checkpoint-backed`, do not\n  synthesize the Summary/Changes sections from empty Entire data. Switch the\n  whole PR-content path to the git-only fallback in §Fallback for both title\n  and body.\n\n- **Body** uses this fixed template:\n\n  ```markdown\n  ## Summary\n\n  <2–4 sentences synthesized from the per-commit intents>\n\n  ## Changes\n\n  - <commit-subject> — <one-line \"why\" from entire explain --short>\n  - <commit-subject> — <one-line \"why\" from entire explain --short>\n\n  ## Test plan\n\n  - [ ] <derived from `git diff --stat` against merge-base>\n  ```\n\n  - The Summary paragraph is synthesized by the agent from the collected\n    per-commit summaries. It is NOT a literal concatenation.\n  - \"Changes\" lists each commit in chronological order. Mixed-author branches\n    naturally show some commits with rich `entire`-derived \"why\" and some with\n    just the subject — that's fine and informative.\n  - The Test plan checklist is derived from `git diff --stat <merge-base>..HEAD`\n    file types (e.g., touched `*.ts` → \"type-check + test the affected\n    component\"; touched `*.go` → \"go test + go vet\"). This mirrors the\n    upstream skill. This repo does not currently have a checked-in PR template,\n    so the skill must define the body shape itself.\n\n### 6. Open or update the PR\n\n- Run `gh pr view --json number,isDraft,state` for the current branch.\n  - If a PR exists with `state == \"OPEN\"`: update title and body via\n    `gh pr edit`. Do **not** toggle draft state if the PR is already non-draft\n    (avoid surprising the user).\n  - If a PR exists but is `CLOSED` or `MERGED`: ignore it and fall through to\n    create a fresh draft PR. Do not reopen or edit a closed/merged PR.\n  - If `gh pr view` exits non-zero (no PR found): create a fresh draft PR.\n- Create path: `gh pr create --draft --title ... --body ...`. Always `--draft`\n  per the user's global preference.\n\n### 7. Print the PR URL\n\nEcho the PR URL as the final output.\n\n## Fallback (no `entire` data)\n\nIf `entire` is not installed, not configured for the repo, or returned no\ncheckpoint-backed data for any commit in the push range, fall back to the\ngit-only path: `git diff HEAD` + `git log <merge-base>..HEAD` to build commit\nmessage and PR body. The fallback is silent (no error) — it just produces a\ngit-only PR, exactly like upstream.\n\n## Resolved questions\n\n1. **Slash command or flag on the existing one?** New skill. The upstream\n   `commit-commands` plugin is third-party and shouldn't be forked-in-place.\n2. **Where does it live?** This repo (`/Users/alisha/Projects/skills`) under\n   `skills/commit-push-pr/SKILL.md`. Same convention as the four existing\n   skills (`explain`, `what-happened`, `search`, `session-handoff`). Cross-\n   agent distribution is already wired up via the plugin metadata in\n   `.claude-plugin/`, `.agents/plugins/`, `.codex-plugin/`, etc.\n3. **Skill name & invocation.** Name: `commit-push-pr`. Plugin-namespaced\n   invocation is `entire:commit-push-pr`, mirroring upstream\n   `commit-commands:commit-push-pr`. The names collide in unscoped form, but\n   the namespace prefix disambiguates and the user opted into both.\n4. **`--since` window for dispatch fallback.** Time of the oldest commit in\n   the push range, computed via `git log --reverse --format=%aI\n   <merge-base>..HEAD | head -1`. Subtract a 1-hour buffer so checkpoints\n   created shortly before the first commit are still included. The buffer is\n   tolerated because dispatch fallback only fires for branches with >10\n   commits, where the window is wide regardless.\n5. **Run `entire explain --generate` on the fly?** **No** for v1. It can be\n   slow and requires API credentials. Missing summaries fall through to the\n   commit subject. We can add an opt-in `--generate-missing` flag in v2.\n6. **Mixed-author branches.** No special handling. Commits without\n   checkpoints surface as bare commit subjects in the \"Changes\" list. This\n   is the right UX — humans see exactly which commits had agent context and\n   which didn't.\n7. **Existing PR on the branch.** Update via `gh pr edit`, do not create a\n   second PR. Do not change draft state of a PR that is already non-draft.\n8. **Per-commit lookup cap.** 10. Branches with more commits use a single\n   `entire dispatch --local` call instead of 10+ per-commit calls. This\n   keeps latency bounded and matches the upstream skill's \"one round-trip\"\n   ergonomic.\n9. **Which files carry the release version?** Keep every versioned manifest in\n   sync: `package.json`, `gemini-extension.json`,\n   `.claude-plugin/plugin.json`, `.claude-plugin/marketplace.json`,\n   `.codex-plugin/plugin.json`, and `.cursor-plugin/plugin.json`.\n\n## SKILL.md shape\n\nThe skill file follows the same structure as the existing four skills:\n\n- Frontmatter: `name` (`commit-push-pr`), `description` (a triggering blurb\n  that names the action and the value of using `entire` context).\n- A `## Response Format` section that mirrors `explain`, `search`,\n  `session-handoff`, and `what-happened`: begin the first successful response\n  with the literal line `Entire Commit:` followed by a blank line. Apply the\n  header to the first response of the invocation only; omit it on early-exit\n  or error responses (e.g. `gh` missing, not in a repo, push refused).\n- A `## Process` section listing the seven steps in §Behavior verbatim.\n- Body target: ~120–180 lines. This is longer than upstream's 20-line slash\n  command because the SKILL has to be self-contained for cross-agent runtimes\n  that lack Claude-Code-style `allowed-tools` frontmatter or single-message\n  batched-tool-call ergonomics. Still well under `what-happened`'s 333 lines.\n- No prose explaining *why* the skill exists — that goes in the README, not\n  the SKILL.\n\n## Repo updates needed\n\n- New file: `skills/commit-push-pr/SKILL.md`.\n- README update: add a section under `## Skills` describing the new skill,\n  matching the format used for `explain`, `what-happened`, etc.\n- README \"Quick Start\" examples: add a couple of natural-language triggers\n  (e.g., \"open a PR with entire context\", \"commit and PR this work\").\n- Bump the release version to `0.4.0` in every versioned manifest:\n  `package.json`, `gemini-extension.json`, `.claude-plugin/plugin.json`,\n  `.claude-plugin/marketplace.json`, `.codex-plugin/plugin.json`, and\n  `.cursor-plugin/plugin.json`.\n- Update `.opencode/INSTALL.md` so its pinned-version example uses the same\n  release tag (`#v0.4.0`) as the manifests in this PR.\n- No schema or path changes to `.claude-plugin/`, `.agents/plugins/`, or other\n  distribution metadata — they already point at `./skills/` and will discover\n  the new skill file automatically once it exists.\n\n## Delivery\n\n**Single PR.** This is a self-contained addition: one new SKILL.md, README\nupdate, and synchronized manifest version bumps. Estimated diff still well\nunder 250 lines.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\nThe PR is mergeable when:\n\n1. `skills/commit-push-pr/SKILL.md` exists with valid frontmatter discovered\n   by Claude Code, Codex, Gemini, OpenCode, Cursor, Copilot, and Antigravity\n   (per the existing distribution paths in the README).\n2. Manual smoke test on this repo: invoke the skill on a branch with at least\n   two checkpoint-backed commits and verify the resulting draft PR has\n   per-commit \"why\" bullets sourced from `entire explain`.\n3. Manual smoke test of the fallback: simulate missing `entire` without\n   mutating the developer's installed binary (for example by overriding `PATH`\n   for the invocation or inserting a temporary shim that exits 127), invoke the\n   skill, and verify it produces a git-only PR equivalent to upstream.\n4. README cross-references the upstream skill so users understand when to\n   pick one over the other.\n5. All six versioned manifests report the same release version after the\n   change, and the pinned OpenCode install example in `.opencode/INSTALL.md`\n   matches that release tag.\n\n## Out of scope\n\n- Modifying the `entire` CLI itself.\n- Anything that requires the `entire` server / `entire search`.\n- Replacing or modifying the upstream `commit-commands:commit-push-pr`.\n- A v2 `--generate-missing` flag (deferred).\n- Worktree-aware behavior (default `git push`/`gh pr` semantics already\n  handle worktrees cor