le decision.\n   - `entire explain <checkpoint-id> --short --no-pager` — optional checkpoint\n     detail for the most recent current-branch checkpoint when synthesizing a\n     commit message for newly staged but uncommitted work.\n   - `entire dispatch --local --since <window>` — prose summary of recent agent\n     work for the current branch. **Optional tiebreaker only** (see\n     §\"Design choice: per-commit, not dispatch\" below).\n   - `entire activity` / `entire sessions` — not used in the core flow.\n\n2. Always pass `--no-pager` to `entire explain` calls so explain output stays\n   non-interactive in agent shells. Do not invent `--no-pager` on commands that\n   do not support it (for example `entire dispatch`).\n\n3. Use the installed `entire` from `PATH`, not a `./entire` checked into the\n   repo.\n\n## Design choice: per-commit, not dispatch\n\nThe earlier draft proposed `entire dispatch --local` as the primary source for\nthe PR title and body summary. I'm pushing back. Reasons:\n\n- `dispatch` is **time-window scoped** (`--since`/`--until`), not commit-range\n  scoped. A branch that sat for a few days alongside other work will pull in\n  unrelated agent activity from sibling branches.\n- `dispatch` is designed for standup-style activity reports, not for \"describe\n  this set of commits\".\n- Per-commit `entire explain --commit <sha> --short` already gives precise,\n  branch-scoped context. Aggregating those across the push range is more\n  faithful to the actual diff being reviewed.\n\n**Decision:** the skill aggregates `entire explain --commit <sha> --short` for\nevery commit in the push range. `entire dispatch --local` is only invoked as a\nfallback when the push range has more than `MAX_PER_COMMIT_LOOKUPS` commits\n(proposed cap: 10). In every other case, dispatch is skipped. (An earlier draft\nalso suggested falling back to dispatch when every per-commit lookup returned\n\"no checkpoint\"; that trigger was dropped because dispatch reads the same\ncheckpoint store and would be equally empty.)\n\n## Behavior the skill should produce\n\nThe skill executes the following sequence. Independent commands inside a step\nshould be batched in parallel where the host agent supports it.\n\n### 1. Sanity / preflight\n\n- Run `entire version` and `gh --version`. If `entire` is missing → fall back\n  to git-only path (see §Fallback). If `gh` is missing → stop with a clear\n  error.\n- Run `git rev-parse --is-inside-work-tree`. If not in a repo, stop.\n- Determine the base branch:\n  1. `gh repo view --json defaultBranchRef -q .defaultBranchRef.name` if\n     authenticated.\n  2. Otherwise `git symbolic-ref --short refs/remotes/origin/HEAD` and strip\n     the `origin/` prefix.\n  3. Otherwise `main`.\n- Compute the merge-base: `git merge-base origin/<base> HEAD`. If\n  `origin/<base>` is missing, fetch it once with `git fetch origin <base>` and\n  retry. If still missing, stop and ask the user.\n- Do **not** finalize the push range yet if the working tree is dirty. A new\n  commit created in Step 3 would otherwise be missing from the PR summary.\n\n### 2. Branch from `main` if needed\n\nIf the current branch IS the base branch, create a new branch first. Derive the\nbranch name from the same heuristics later used for the commit message seed in\nStep 3, sanitized to `kebab-case` and prefixed with `agent/`. If that seed is\nempty or too vague, fall back to `agent/<YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS>`. Do not ask the user\nto pick a branch name in v1.\n\n### 3. Stage + commit any uncommitted work\n\n- `git status --porcelain` to detect uncommitted changes. Skip this step if\n  clean.\n- Stage with explicit paths (no `git add -A`/`git add .`) per the user's\n  global git-safety rules.\n- Build the commit message seed:\n  - First inspect `entire explain --no-pager` list output for the newest\n    checkpoint on the current branch. If a relevant checkpoint is present, run\n    `entire explain <checkpoint-id> --short --no-pager` and use its intent line\n    as the seed.\n  - If there is no relevant checkpoint, or the checkpoint intent clearly does\n    not match the staged diff, fall back to a `git diff --staged` summary (same\n    path the upstream skill takes).\n- `git commit -m \"$(cat <<'EOF' ... EOF)\"` with the standard `Co-Authored-By`\n  trailer.\n- After committing, recompute the push range with\n  `git log --reverse --format=%H <merge-base>..HEAD` so the freshly created\n  commit is included in the PR content.\n\n### 4. Push\n\n- `git push -u origin HEAD`.\n\n### 5. Build the PR content\n\n- For each commit SHA in the push range, run in parallel:\n  `entire explain --commit <sha> --short --no-pager`.\n- Deduplicate per-checkpoint output where multiple commits share a checkpoint.\n- For each commit, classify the result:\n  - `checkpoint-backed` — has an intent/summary line.\n  - `no-checkpoint` — commit was authored outside an Entire session (human\n    commit, manual rebase, etc.). Detected by matching the literal output\n    `No associated Entire checkpoint` (or its `--short` equivalent), or by a\n    zero-exit run that produced no intent line. Use the commit message subject\n    verbatim.\n  - `lookup-failed` — non-zero exit. Log to stderr, treat as `no-checkpoint`.\n\n- **Title** — derived from the *most recent* `checkpoint-backed` commit's\n  intent, trimmed to ≤70 chars. If no commit is checkpoint-backed, fall back\n  to the upstream skill's git-derived title.\n- If **zero** commits in the push range are `checkpoint-backed`, do not\n  synthesize the Summary/Changes sections from empty Entire data. Switch the\n  whole PR-content path to the git-only fallback in §Fallback for both title\n  and body.\n\n- **Body** uses this fixed template:\n\n  ```markdown\n  ## Summary\n\n  <2–4 sentences synthesized from the per-commit intents>\n\n  ## Changes\n\n  - <commit-subject> — <one-line \"why\" from entire explain --short>\n  - <commit-subject> — <one-line \"why\" from entire explain --short>\n\n  ## Tes